181508740.description: This is a series of exploration using wet charcoal to capture the atmosphere and energy of the environment. The painting was mostly done with fast brush stroke in the dark and aiming to reconstruct the blurry memory of the scene.
181508740.title: So Light, So Thin

181512004.description: This Project is an apparatus that allows for the registration of land forming geological processes in Boston throughout time, both past and future, and throughout the history of debate and observation (including photography, painting, and physical modelling) by the naturalists Louis Agassiz, Henry David Thoreau, landscape architect Frederick Law Olmsted, and others speculating during the 19th century. The circle, a closure of the Emerald Necklace acts as a physical register of the land: sometimes a cut, a walkway, or a wall and marked by lightweight interventions that serve as oculii placing focus on these histories. While a past history can be made known, the future is only tenuously predictable. As waters are predicted to rise, the circle will register a new process of land loss.
181512004.title: Thompson Island

184131588.description: Drawing is one of the only way I find to relax. Every piece represents a state of mind of a given moment in my life. Every drawing changes significantly in appearance before I’m done with it. I usually put several layers of marker/paint before I’m happy with it. In some way this is similar to the iteration process required to build successful startups!
184131588.title: EDSO

184134084.description: The Layered Superquadra takes the premise of the typological Brasilia housing block, the superquadra, and creates a mixed-use urban development by lifting the form of the superquadra onto a mixed-use institutional plinth. The two-storey plinth is composed of retail program lining the block at ground level, a horizontal open-plan office bracketing the second floor, and the two story museum occupying the center of the block. This monumental plaza functions both as an extension of the museum as an open sculpture garden, as well as an urban gathering space lined with restaurants.
184134084.title: The Layered Superquadra

184895876.description: This series explores an architectural possibility to place a fluid urban theatre in downtown Boston. At the intersection of a subway station, music school and residential blocks, the idea of an enclave gives an identity to the urban landscape. I am a graduate student at MIT, pursuing dual degrees in architecture and real estate development.
184895876.title: Commune

184897028.description: As one cycles through the streets of Bedford-Stuyvesant in Brooklyn, one immediately discerns repercussions of the constant expansion and shrinking of cities. Vacant lots are compressed on both sides by buildings, which paradoxically highlight the voids, the emptiness. A parallel city appears, one of voids, transience and ephemerality. This city has few informal occupants: dealers, prostitutes and homeless, but also community gardens, block parties, a chicken coop, and an unofficial mechanic’s shop. One wonders ‘how can architecture shelter the residents of the interim city?‘
184897028.title: Migrating Festivities

185009092.description: The Shēngxiào, literally "birth likeness", is also known in English as the Chinese zodiac. Zodiac derives from the similar concept in western astrology and means "circle of animals". The Chinese zodiac is a scheme and systematic plan of future action that relates each year to an animal and its reputed attributes according to a 12-year cycle. This series emphasized the combination and juxtaposition of architectural sequences of space and an animal’s bone structure.
185009092.title: Chinese Zodiac

185010180.description: A supernatural dreamlike world, Iceland is home to some of the most breathtaking alien-like landscapes on earth. In celebration of Earth Day 2015. Marwan Aboudib, exhibits his photographs of his trip last winter. His aim was to capture the impact global warming has had on the majestic land of volcanoes and glaciers. As the planet heats up, Iceland’s largest glacier Vatnajokull has been retreating through global warming and volcanic eruptions. In the series exhibited, the glacial breakdown process of the massive glacier Svinajokull is shown. The glacier is famous for being filmed in the award winning movie Interstellar and as the hunting grounds of the White Walkers in the television series, Game of Thrones.
185010180.title: Arctic Heat

185233604.title: Mental Prism

185243972.description: This collection of images are both of algorithmically computed physical machine-made models and computer generated 3D digital models. 185243972.title: Fashion, Architecture & Textiles

185326596.description: The featured bird and flower share the same name, "Bird of Paradise." The flowers look incredibly like the head of the rather exotic crested bird and its feathers. Geographically, they don’t have any connection, with the bird residing in X and the flower growing in Y, and yet the similarities are astounding. The goal of my piece is to connect these two beautiful species and celebrate the coincidence of nature.
185326596.title: Birds of Paradise

185329092.description: I never like to name any of my artworks because each person sees something different in every abstract piece. Whatever each individual sees is what that artwork is, only look at the title if you need inspiration!
185329092.title: Hallucinations

185330564.description: A thriller story staged at Mies’ Farnsworth House. As a new analytical method, 12 narrative prints thread together the design features, contextual environment and key historical moments of the masterpiece. The black and white linoleum prints also intend to portray the Film Noir atmosphere that were once popular in the Hollywood crime dramas in 50s and 60s.
185330564.title: Narrative Farnsworth

185331268.description: The theatre has always been described as reflecting social mechanisms and ideology, and urban space is often set out as a theatrical show. As indicated in Ledoux’s engraving, the auditorium is reflected in a giant pupil, indicating the reversible relationship between the actor and the spectator. Ledoux compared the ample dimensions of the stage to the space outside, and ultimately to the city. Both the theatre and public space are venues for assemblage and exchange of knowledge and ideas. The engagement can also be better achieved by reducing the distance between the actor and the audience, as suggested by the futurists, who aimed to subvert traditional bourgeois drama. They proposed to turn the traditional theater inside out by extending the stage and allowing the audience to interact with the actor, which allows for more improvisations and provocations (Kirby and Kirby 43). The avant-garde theater movement also proposed to abolish the stage or separation it implies. They welcomed a unique site without borders or barriers. Spectators were anticipated to join the kind of collective creation. As the futurists claimed that reality vibrates around us, hitting us with bursts of fragments with events among them, embedded one with the other, confused, entangled, and chaotic.
185331268.title: A Theather Without Theater

185332932.description: A "moment" is something unique – a combination of subject, place and time that cannot be repeated. Every moment has a story, from the curious eyes of a girl watching me leave after we played rock-paper-scissor in the rural China, or the brother and sister playing with water at the side of the sacred pool in the middle of Pushkar, India. With this collection, I want to make you feel “there” with me and imagine the story around such a moment.
185332932.title: Moments

185334916.description: By expanding your horizons and opening up yourself, a real connection between you and the world is established. Nothing like great “views” can make you feel so small, yet so much part of this planet, and the same feeling of belonging is triggered from both the largest salt desert in Uyuni, Bolivia and the dazzling skyline of Hong Kong. With this collection, I want you to feel part of this world, and take in the gorgeous views it has to offer.
185334916.title: Views

185336068.description: And so the story of Agapios begins... a blind man living in 256 A.D. Chalcis, Greece discovers sight through traveling. Experiencing foreign environments and meeting unique creatures, he identifies the presence of new codes, and discovers a universal language. His travels end at the top of a mountain above An Imperfect City, which pushes him to accept contradiction and embrace the beauty of incompleteness.
185336068.title: The Wandering Blind Man: An Architectural Fiction

185466052.description: This series illustrates different ideas for the product development of Woboo, a child-companion robot. Woboo is currently being prototyped at MIT by a group of students. I am the lead designer for the project and these drawings show different interactions between a child and Woboo. I use the ball point pen and marker to quickly draw multiple iterations and communicate concepts to the team.
185466052.title: Woobo - Concept Sketch

185466436.description: Water color as a medium of design, and animation as a means of representation attempt at departing from 20th century deterministic modalities of production. Here, I establish a system of parameters for which the medium of watercolor adopts the role of designer in the settling of densities and viscosities of ink in water on canvas, parameters which imply new forms of spatial, social and formal organization. From a discrete point of view, the camp organization is set up by nodes, which respond to a specific set of criteria. Each node, consists of 250-500 inhabitants, containing its own programmatic ecosystem. The design is then to associate space and time with the resulting water-color forms, redistributing an a priori index of operations to an a posteriori reasoning and discovering the possibilities offered by the gradianted nature of the generating medium. The game becomes interpreting, forming, re-interpreting and re-forming with the aim of maintaining the original implications of the watercolor plan which suggest an architectural and social structure that is heterogeneous in form, non-discrete in nature. The gradient change in color can be seen by the gradianting phase changes over time (animation), as the energies arrives at an equilibrium, but which is still an interface that is internally dynamic.
185466436.title: Liquid Urbanism

185469124.description: These images are the result of scripting experiments exploring point-cloud painting techniques. Striving to promote design inquiry and technological research across the scales of software, objects, discourse, buildings, and cities, I use technology to invigorate thought to surpass boundaries, catalyze solutions, and collaboratively address the challenges of urban-dwelling. My work mashes-up high and low technologies, mixes critical analysis with speculation, and seeks collaboration with a plethora of third parties - a flexible recipe for imaginative and empowering interventions.
185469124.title: Point-Cloud Paintings

185782916.description: Beyond this layer, the project also challenges the relationship between permanentness and temporariness, in particular the housing typology. By introducing the portable housing subdivision to lower level of each housing unit, the project releases the freedom of both physical and mental relocation to the future residents. The aggregation of housing units, public spaces and enclosed courtyards is fully dissolved within the Marfa context and most significantly, creates an active dialogue between the nature, the artists and the whole local community.
185782916.title: Freewheeling Suburbia

185786820.description: Since 1960, Ghana has been run by 6 different presidents. Starting off with dr. H. C. Kwame Nkrumah, who didn’t only set a standard in Ghana but also outside its borders, as he paved the way for many other African countries to follow.  After him there have been other leaders, who have been very significant in Ghana’s ‘upbringing’-Jerry John Rawlings, who led one of the most controversial coups in Ghana, which was a major turning point in the country’s history.  However i feel our presidents aren’t honored enough, it’s either you’ve heard about them or not. I really don’t blame our educational system entirely for this, because people cannot be spoon fed with this kind of information all the time. But i do feel that this kind of information could be 'stumbled upon’ if it was actually made noticeable in the country. There are only a few memorials for these veterans, and that could be a reason why people know very little or know nothing about these people. That is why i came up with the presidential series, to shed some light on these veterans. The design of the work was most important to me, because I had to re-create images of the various presidents that are going to make up this book. I started off with Kwame Nkrumah, mainly because he was the first president of Ghana. What I did was to graphically paint their portraits with shapes, ultimately comprised of triangles, to create an unorthodox way of painting portraits. this I feel, is quite eye catching and able to draw enough attention for viewers to question not only how it was made, but why it was made in the first place. also painting it in red was another conscious decision, as I wanted to go for an out of the ordinary color, and sort of shy away from local color to draw more attention to the book.
185786820.title: Neoblocks

185853956.description: The artwork shows plans for a mega-structure to be built on top of the existing Boston fish factory. The design intent and inspiration is based on a radical approach where human labor is replaced with machinery, similar to the Futurist interpretations of the 1920’s. Having grown-up in Middle East, the unprecedented speed off Dubai’s urbanization and the reawakening of post-war Beirut has shaped my vision for the integration of architectural design and real estate development. The design enhances the existing infrastructure of pier by adapting the architecture to future growth of the city.
185853956.title: SupraeXtructure

185854468.description: The Happy Prince is a short story for children by Oscar Wilde first published in 1888. The Happy Prince is a statue with a kind heart and sympathy. With the help of a swallow who was left behind from his flock, he sends all the valuable parts from his body to poor people who are suffering. The two illustrations Jun Cen created capture the humanity and melancholy of the story with his unique visual language.
185854468.title: Happy Prince

185857156.description: These photographs capture an experiment on chess figures. These were designed during a studio at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (M.I.T). As a former chess champion, I am quite fond of the game and its intricacies. In chess, hierarchy is expressed through the symbolism of the pieces. The project is a reinterpretation of that hierarchy. With strategic form shifts on each chess figure, a fluid and amorphous image was achieved, while conserving the key gesture for each figure. All the pieces of the set were 3D printed.
185857156.title: Chess Army

185866948.description: The last decades rapid increase in mobility and the deployment of the internet in all spheres of living and working has produced unprecedented changes in occupancy. The case of the office space as a typology is very interesting as it continues to be extremely permeable to changes in society. The internet has deeply transformed collaboration patterns and challenged hierarchical managerial patterns. There is a belief that social interaction itself can be a source of knowledge production. So my project hypothesis is to rethink the work space as a distinct building typology.
185866948.title: Coexistence of Complementary Enterprises

185868100.description: This project is interested in the morphology between the contemporary Chinese city the diverse modes of socialization. How the city is organized the urban life it produces. The context in the urban village of Shenzhen, a constantly changing environment. The extreme density of the urban village, juxtaposition of living working space, results in frequent interactions vibrant activities. The sharing of space is rooted in the tradition of urban village, leading to the close bounding in the community.
185868100.title: Urban Morphology

185868804.description: As a scientific discipline, archaeology deals with the factual, with rational arguments and identifiable sources. But archaeology is most relevant and interesting when it transcends factual description and engages speculation and imagination. Out of 30 boreholes that go down to 30m on the site of King’s Cross, we have chosen the borehole “I” to study the components of ground and the description of each component. Importantly, we focused not only the “official” definition of the material, but on the colloquial usage of the language that describes it, the folk sayings.
185868804.title: Archaeologists Are Storytellers

185872068.description: ‘Protected Entrance’ is a protection infrastructure constructed by roots of Banyan and Glass trees. The areas surrounding sinkholes are warmer and humid due to the chemical reactions of limestone. This condition allows these types of tropical tree root to grow faster. The roots of Banyan tend to expand horizontally, and the roots of Looking Glass tree expand vertically. Therefore, these two root systems create a cross net to support the structure of the land. Moreover, the air root of Banyan will grow faster toward the center of the humid sinkhole and form a unique gesture at the surface. It becomes a signal in the landscape.
185872068.title: Protected Entrance

185873028.description: The Karst landscape of central Florida is covered with sinkholes, caused by the collapse of the ground into a vast system of underground limestone caves. These sinkholes activities cause land subsidence and accelerate flooding in Florida. Geologists predict that 70% place of central Florida will become a huge wet land connected to everglade in the future. People who live in this area keep using piers, grouting, and underpinning to strength the ground structure. However, these ways are not a good long term solution in nature time scale. This thesis will turn the disaster into an opportunity for Architecture by creating a series of infrastructural prototypes work with the natural forces of this extreme landform.
185873028.title: Looking Down to the Land

186619652.description: Seoul City Interface’ was a studio project conducted at the Harvard School of Design. The aim of the project was to create and develop a digital platform that would serve to translate and transform digital experiences and activities into the physical and spatial real within the context of Seoul, South Korea. The pieces show various typologies of public space what would ultimately hold host to digital interventions around the city. Using composite techniques that involved hand-drawn and watercolor elements, as well as digital, computer based means. The images evoke and establish a certain quality and visual character that communicated and represented the identity of the project.

My collages are defragmentations of cities, separating in layers different physical aspects and intangible concepts of a certain place.
186620356.title: Vanishing Point

186692228.description: ‘Rawbijou’, part of ‘Collection Platinum’, is a play on lines and winding architectural hoops. Drawing in metal: on and around a woman’s body. It explores notions of positive and negative space, by using the female body as a site to sculpt out morphed geometries while paying particular attention to body language. The easily stackable rings, draw on your fingers with expressive lines, volumes, and silhouettes of gold, blurring the line between body art and jewelry.The collection takes the hooped earring form in classic jewelry as a starting point, redesigning it into a modern hoop wave form. The single hoop earrings are made for the girl who can never find her ‘other earring’. While the single hoop ear-cuffs are designed with the girl who hates long dangly earrings in mind. No piercings are needed; it simply hugs your ear for an asymmetric playful look. The single pearl earrings however, are an ‘ode to Vermeer’. Like miniature pieces of architecture, the pearl levitates within its rhodium frame, and is finally trapped to fit on to the ear. The contrasting nature of the classic pearl with the modern rhodium frame creates a contradictory conversation piece.
186692228.title: Rawbijou

There, she also worked for its sister company, another MIT startup that built the world’s leading platform for solar rooftop mapping. Prior to Boston, Naomi was hired at internationally recognized architecture offices in New York and Paris. She currently handles Tekuma’s logistics and art curation.

wZVi3jjgWXTRDOy7PUtTYSgXPbY2.bio:
An Architect, Photographer, Visual Storyteller
A Seeker, Inquirer, Questioner, and Researcher

Native to California, George X. Lin received his Bachelors degree from UC Berkeley and completed his Masters of Architecture at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He is a register Architect in the state of California. Exploring and experiencing new environments has always been his fascination. While growing up in California, he was blessed to be in close proximity to nature. However, at the time he did not realize how fortunate he was to be surrounded by nature and all its beauties, partly because many people in his life fantasized instead about exotic countries abroad. While George was fascinated by his travels abroad, these travels led him to realize that the same diversity exists here in his backyard. The only requirement to discovering this diversity was occasionally venturing off the beaten path and exploring. He truly believes that we have to learn to get lost so that we can find ourselves.

5048365636.title: The Wandering Blind Man: An Architectural Fiction - I

shopify.body_html:
by Jonathan Rohrbough

''And so the story of Agapios begins... a blind man living in 256 A.D. Chalcis, Greece discovers sight through traveling. Experiencing foreign environments and meeting unique creatures, he identifies the presence of new codes, and discovers a universal language. His travels end at the top of a mountain above An Imperfect City, which pushes him to accept contradiction and embrace the beauty of incompleteness.''

Jonny received his Bachelors in Architecture at the University of Michigan, and studied the integration of architecture, painting, and sculpture at SAIC. He challenges the notion that architects should produce a definite object, and hopes to inspire a culture of creativity and non-conformity through imagination and criticism.
